The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee on Thursday left for Vietnam on a two-day visit. He is being accompanied by principal secretary Dipankar Mukhopadhyay and a team of nine industrialists, among others. The industrialists include Rajeev Kaul, Roopen Roy of PricewaterhouseCoopers and CII regional chairman Ravi Poddar. 

 he chief minister will visit the Tan Tao industrial zone, and meet the chairman of the Ho Chi Minh City People?s Committee and representatives of the Vietnam Chamber of Commerce and Industry. 

 A Calcutta High Court division bench on Thursday acquitted Niamuddin Sheikh, who had been sentenced to life imprisonment by the Alipore court for allegedly murdering a housewife, Begam Ara, by setting her on fire. The division bench of Justice A.K. Basu and Justice P.K.Deb observed that Sheikh, a resident of Garden Reach, was convicted on the basis of indirect evidence.

 n May 9, 2000, Begam Ara was found ablaze at her residence in Garden Reach. In her dying declaration, she told doctors that she wanted to commit suicide. However, her 12-year-old son later lodged a complaint that he had seen Sheikh setting her mother on fire.

 An armed criminal snatched a gold chain from a woman, after failing to snatch her handbag, in Birati, on the northern fringes of the city, on Thursday afternoon. Police said Namita Dasgupta was returning home after drawing her salary, which she kept in the handbag. Near Birati station, the criminal appeared from behind and tried to snatch the bag. He failed as Namita held the bag tightly, but managed to snatch the chain.

 Calcutta High Court on Wednesday allowed the Children Welfare Committee to dispose of the matter relating to Rima Singh and Puja Singh, arrested on charges of immoral trafficking. Justice S.P. Talukdar said the committee need not take the consent of the metropolitan magistrate?s court if it wanted to hand over the girls to their parents. 

 he order followed a petition by Rituparna De, counsel for Rima?s parents, alleging that the committee was not releasing the girls even after ossification tests proved that they were not minors. The panel reportedly told Rima?s parents that it could not release the girls without the metropolitan magistrate?s consent.

 Amitabha Roy, 64, was found dead in front of his house in Barrackpore, on the northern fringes of the city, on Thursday morning. Police suspect Roy had been suffering from depression because of some ailments. The body has been sent for post-mortem. 

 A person was injured after a cylinder exploded in a food stall at Rashmoni Market, in Baruipur, on the southern fringes of the city, on Thursday evening. He was admitted to a local hospital in a serious condition. The stall was gutted.

 Alleged extortionist Hafizul Haq managed to give police the slip at Bibir Bagan More, in Chitpore, on Thursday afternoon. Officers said a patrolling police van spotted him and gave chase, but he managed to flee. 

